When a small group of living organisms (one small population) separates from the main population they came from (such as if they are floating over a mountain range or a river, or if they move to another island, making it difficult for them to return) they often find themselves in an environment other than the one from which appeared.
This new environment has different resources and other competitors making the new population need other characteristics or adaptations to become a strong competitor than those needed before.
The original population has not changed at all and they need to continue the same adaptations as before.
Over time, the new population has started to adapt to their new environments, resulting in more and more differences in the second population.
Finally, after thousands or millions of years, the two populations will be so different that they cannot be called the same species.
We call this process to specie of species formation which means the formation of new species.[citation needed]
